Node.Notes: ""[A psalm/song] to the servant of the Lord, [namely] David, which he sang ...""
Horn is a metaphor for strength and power . Phrase as whole something like "the mighty champion who saves me."
Uncertain. Tree assumes something like: I will call on the one who is worthy to be praised, namely Yahweh.
Uncertain. Assumes adjective as substantive. Could assume perfect 3ms verb with elision: [the day when] trouble was to … , which is spelled out in ps59:17 and 102:3.
Uncertain. Tree assumes "[he sets the darkness of waters, i.e., the clouds of skies, as his canopy around him."
Tree assumes these phenomenon (not naturally associated) advance (carrying over verb from first half) before God's glorious presence.
Coals of fire, which causes difficulty, because these are not associated with a thunderstorm (hence some go with bolts of lightning, seeing the brightness from first half as lightning).
Many omit "hailstone and coals of fire," but tree assumes "he gives" in the sense of sends out, from first previous clause carried over.
Coals of fire should probably be retained as this is a theophany and not a natural phenomenon where coals of fire could not be associated with a thunderstorm.
